jvmArg, and for native, it's a bit different since no installation occurs there. I'll check the build.gradle to ensure the nativeTest configuration is set correctly and remove any unnecessary SecurityManager usage.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Designing the test case**\\n\\nI need to create a test for `FinalizableReferenceQueueInnerDecoupledLoaderTest`. In the test, I'm checking if the queue initializes correctly through the decoupled finalizer loader when the system loader can't resolve the finalizer. If the system loader is a DenyFinalizerSystemClassLoader, I might need to reset it and assert that the finalizer was indeed denied. However, it's possible that the system loader has already initialized, which could affect my assertions. To be safe, I might skip checking if it was denied and focus on ensuring there's no previous initialization of the queue.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Assessing custom loader behavior**\\n\\nI need to consider that the custom loader denial might trigger on the first initialization somewhere, which could affect active call sites if any tests trigger the `FinalizableReferenceQueue` after startup. The existing `FinalizerTest` could run before the custom loader is initialized, which is concerning. If the class is imported, it won't initialize unless there's static analysis, which I think isn't the case here. Maybe I can use `@TestMethodOrder`, although that might not work across classes. It might be wise to assert conditions only if I check `FinalizableReferenceQueue.class.getClassLoader()`.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering Gradle test process**\\n\\nThe user mentioned to not run something, relating to the previous task about avoiding compilation or tests. It seems I shouldn't run anything risky, especially concerning global `jvmarg`. Instead, I might think about using `-Xbootclasspath/a`, but that may not work here. The Gradle test process probably includes the Gradle worker and not just test classes, so I need to be cautious and consider the implications of my actions.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering build options**\\n\\nI'm thinking about whether to use the build.gradle task to copy a class, but I wonder if that's suitable for source files. I could possibly create a loader as a Java file in `buildSrc`, but then again, maybe that’s not worth the effort. An alternative could be to utilize `JAVA_TOOL_OPTIONS` during testing, but it's a bit tricky since it only applies at startup. I'm weighing my options here!\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_GprvhqCfLsjPQegi8whkbz8L|fc_04012b1346cd859e0169f653cb0f98819488270ebad2cda7b6", "name": "read", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/com.google.guava/guava/r06/user-code-filter.json"}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 51099, "output": 4400, "cacheRead": 6144, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 61643, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1777750927046, "responseId": "resp_04012b1346cd859e0169f6539021608194a30ceaf735bf4a1b"}}
